1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
 So now I want to talk about the concept of logic gates. So what are logic gates? Well logic gates are not a real thing.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 Transistors are a real thing. A logic gate is an abstraction that we use as hardware designers to greatly simplify our lives.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:23,000
 This is no different than when I was teaching you software and I'm like, "Look at this cool low level way of doing this, that, and the other thing."

4
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 And you're like, "Oh, that's really pretty complex." And then in the next breath, I say,

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:34,000
 "Well, if we extend this object, we get all this work for free." And now our code goes from 75 lines down to two lines.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,000
 And that's kind of how abstractions work. And that's how gates work.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 So gates, we don't need to think about sort of response graphs of input voltages and output voltages. We don't have to think about that.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 That still is a thing. Gates don't make the whole analog problem go away. They just make it so we don't think about it anymore.

9
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:01,000
 And that's a problem that the folks who manufacture these chips have solved in the manufacturing process.

10
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 We pretty much say, "Let's make a gate and then somehow the gates are manufactured out of analog components."

11
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 The way we think about gates is beautiful. We think about zeros and ones, which is very much digital logic.

12
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
 And the concept of digital logic predates computers, absolutely.

13
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 And so we just say, "Oh, this gate, this NOT gate, if presented with an input of zero, gives an output of one.

14
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
 And if it's presented with an input of one, it gives an output of zero." And that's a NOT gate.

15
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:34,000
 And I like starting with a NOT gate. First, it's the simplest thing. We can see how it's built from transistors.

16
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 But it also is like it's active. It's doing something. It's not just copying something.

17
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:46,000
 So we'll build much more complex logic circuits. We're going to see much more complex gates.

18
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:51,000
 But I can't really run away from history quite yet.

19
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 Over time, as manufacturing capabilities changed from PMOS to NMOS to CMOS,

20
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:06,000
 the way we built a logic gate underneath the abstraction, all these logic gates have an input of A and an output of OUT.

21
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:12,000
 If you put a zero at A, you get a one at OUT. If you could put a one at A, you get a zero at OUT.

22
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 And so there are three symbols. Like the VDD, there's like a 9-volt battery that has its positive terminal at VDD,

23
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
 and its negative terminal at the little ground symbol at the bottom.

24
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:29,000
 The other thing we see is a PMOS transistor. At the top there, it's a transistor.

25
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 It's kind of implying that there's a switch going on or a valve if you want.

26
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 The little circle says PMOS, and the lack of little circle says NMOS, and then the bottom thing is a resistor.

27
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 And it's probably easiest to talk about these in the concept of how they work.

28
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:53,000
 So if you present a zero, let's start with the PMOS in 1972, you present a zero at the input.

29
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:58,000
 That means that the PMOS transistor conducts.

30
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:03,000
 And so that means that the positive voltage is copied to output.

31
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 So when you press a zero, it conducts and it goes to output.

32
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 The PMOS transistor is now conducting both to get the voltage to the output to produce a one at the output,

33
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 but also connecting through the resistor to ground.

34
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 Now every time you see a resistor, it's kind of like a pack.

35
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 And the problem is, is resistors heat up.

36
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:29,000
 But if you didn't have the resistor there, all the little lines, the wires, the tiny wires, and perhaps even the transistor, they would melt.

37
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:37,000
 So the resistors are there to protect the transistors and protect the wires, frankly.

38
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 When NMOS is presented with a zero, that means it's an open circuit.

39
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 And so the nice thing there is when you present it with a zero, it just copies through a resistor, the voltage to the output.

40
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 And the cool thing there is it's not really sending as much current to the output,

41
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,000
 because all that output is being connected to the input of another transistor later in the circuit.

42
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 And so that doesn't really heat up so badly.

43
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 Now if you look at CMOS, what you have is a PMOS transistor at the top and an NMOS transistor at the bottom.

44
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 And they work in pairs.

45
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 And so in the case of the zero, the PMOS transistor conducts and the NMOS transistor doesn't conduct.

46
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 And so there is no resistor and the voltage is copied to the output.

47
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 Now let's look at the case of the one. In PMOS, when you present a one, the PMOS is an open circuit.

48
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 And so that means that we need the output to be zero, which means we have to connect the ground to the output.

49
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 That is connected through a resistor, but it's low current because the output is just going to the input of another transistor.

50
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 And so if you look then at the NMOS, we have the opposite problem when we presented with the one, because the NMOS then conducts,

51
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:03,000
 it both conducts the ground to the output and it conducts the positive to the ground.

52
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 But that would be a short circuit unless we put a resistor there. So there you got a thing heating up.

53
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 So the problem is with PMOS and NMOS, one of the two states for both of them is going to be causing heat.

54
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 One is causing heat on a zero, the other is causing heat on a one.

55
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:27,000
 But then we look at the CMOS. And what we see when we present a one and we want an output of zero,

56
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 well, the NMOS transistor at the bottom is conducting and so ground is connected to the output, which is exactly what we want.

57
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 And the PMOS transistor is an open circuit. So the voltage VDD is not being connected and we don't need a resistor.

58
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:50,000
 And so what you see is there are no resistors and there is just you have to be able to build at a low level

59
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 both PMOS and NMOS transistors in the same circuit, like really tiny.

60
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 And so what happened was this NMOS and PMOS were hot and the hotter they were, the less dense the chips could be.

61
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 So once we went to CMOS, and again, that was really not a question of wanting it.

62
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 It's a question of practical manufacturing.

63
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 And so at some point, mid 1980s, until 486, CMOS became practical.

64
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 All of a sudden, you didn't have to have a central processor the size of a large cabinet.

65
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 And part of that large cabinet had to do with how much power it was taking and how much heat it was generating.

66
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 If you put it all together, it would just like instantly melt.

67
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 And so you had to kind of take these transistors and keep them and resistors in NMOS and PMOS computers

68
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:45,000
 and keep them away from each other because they would overheat because of the resistors.

69
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 But the moment that you can take the size of a computer from 10 feet end to end to one inch end to end, everything got faster.

70
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 So in 1983 is a long time ago.

71
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 There hasn't been a major like upheaval in the talk about like quantum computing and stuff.

72
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 But and that would be a major upheaval at this level.

73
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 But really from 1983 to present, we just pretty much make CMOS because once we could manufacture it reliably, we'll do CMOS.

74
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:27,000
 OK, so now what I want to show you is a tool that that I built called a CMOS layout tool.

75
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:32,000
 And so this way you can connect them and put them together and simulate circuits.

76
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 So let's take a look at this tool.

77
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:42,000
 OK, across the top, we have a number of things that you can place in this circuit and then we'll draw wires in between them.

78
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 So let's start with a probe.

79
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 Here's a probe.

80
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 And if we connect the probe to the positive, you see that the probe is reading that now it's got five volts.

81
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 Now, if we delete that and we place a probe and connect it to the negative, it's zero.

82
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 So part of what we're going to do in the NOT gate is have a switch as input.

83
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 A switch is in effect a switch that either goes to to the positive or the ground.

84
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 And you can imagine there's a wire running up here and a wire running down there.

85
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 But I didn't show that. It's just sort of like another little it's connected either to the top or the bottom so that we can test our circuits.

86
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 So what we're going to do is build a circuit that can create the logic so that whatever we have here as input, the probe on the left as input, we're going to have output that is the opposite of that.

87
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 So these after a while, you get used to these.

88
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:54,000
 So let's first put a PMOS transistor at the top and then put a NMOS transistor below it.

89
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 So we're going to connect the voltage to the top connector of the PMOS transistor.

90
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 And then we're going to connect the bottom connection of the NMOS transistor to ground.

91
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:16,000
 And then we're going to take the output of the NMOS transistor and connect it to the PMOS transistor.

92
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,000
 Now, I say PMOS, the little circle is PMOS and the lack of little circle is NMOS.

93
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 And so the output is going to be connected, it can be connected either place, but the output is basically connected to the connection between the two transistors.

94
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 And then the last thing, the last thing we have to do is connect the switch to the grid of each of these transistors.

95
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 And now we have it. So you can see that it's been sort of adapting and changing.

96
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 And the key thing is, is that the PMOS and NMOS transistors have kind of opposite logic.

97
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:00,000
 So the PMOS here is presented with a 5 volts, which means it's an open circuit.

98
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 And the NMOS is presented with 5 volts, which means it's a closed circuit.

99
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 And that's what this little green line is saying, that it's a closed circuit.

100
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 So if I flip this, it means that the PMOS transistor conducts and the NMOS transistor no longer conducts.

101
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:25,000
 And so now the output is 5 volts because the 5 volts is flowing through the PMOS transistor to the output.

102
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 If I flip it, the PMOS transistor opens up and the ground flows through the NMOS transistor to the output.

103
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 And so that's it. That's the picture that I've been showing you that shows the PMOS and NMOS.

104
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 And there are no resistors in here, so there's no dangerous heat. So I can flip this as fast as I like.

105
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 And you can see it flipping back and forth and it's really activating or closing a closed circuit,

106
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:56,000
 a circuit to close on either the NMOS or the PMOS.

107
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:02,000
 But we've constructed it in a way that it's like an if-then-else for circuit transmission.

108
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:07,000
 And that's why I kind of call this NOT gate, you know, an electrical if statement.

109
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:12,000
 So basically that was a NOT gate and we're going to build much more complex digital gates,

110
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 but then we're going to build circuits out of those gates.

111
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:21,000
 We're not really going to build very complex circuits out of transistors, although ultimately they're manufactured as transistors.

112
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:29,000
 And so there is mathematical logic that predates computers for like AND and OR, exclusive OR and NOT.

113
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:37,000
 And then there's other logic that we kind of learned to use because we could build them with fewer transistors, NAND and NOR.

114
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
 And NAND is NOT AND and NOR is NOR.

115
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:51,000
 So our classic logic gates come from digital logic, something that was a theoretical thing that was penned in paper well before computers came on the scene.

116
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 So the first digital logic gate is a NOT gate that simply inverts its input.

117
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:59,000
 Zero becomes one, one becomes zero.

118
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:01,000
 An AND gate is simple.

119
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 If both of its inputs are one, then the output is one, otherwise the output is zero.

120
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:11,000
 The OR gate is if either of its inputs is one, the output is one.

121
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:14,000
 And if both inputs are zero, the output is zero.

122
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 And then there's the exclusive OR gate, which we're going to find really useful.

123
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 It almost like counts its inputs.

124
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 It's not a counter in any way, but it counts its inputs.

125
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 If one of the inputs is one, its output is one.

126
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 If both the inputs are zero or both the inputs are one, the output of an exclusive OR gate is zero.

127
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 Now, it turns out that we tended to use those AND, OR and NOT in classic digital logic math.

128
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:51,000
 But it turns out that it's easier to build NAND and NOR, which is really an inversion of the AND and inversion of the NOR.

129
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 Now, you could throw a NOT gate on the end of these things to make them be ANDs and ORs.

130
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 But it turned out that early times we just could build NANDs and NORs with a lot fewer transistors.

131
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 And so the NAND gate is the opposite of AND, which means that if any of the inputs of a NAND is zero, the output is a one.

132
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 And if both the inputs of a NAND are one, the output is a zero.

133
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 And similarly for the OR, if both the inputs are zero, the output is a one.

134
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:24,000
 And if any of the inputs of the NOR are one, the output is a zero.

135
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:31,000
 It is literally NOT AND and NOT OR and can be turned into AND and OR with one more NOT gate,

136
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:37,000
 which means that you would put two more transistors at the end of each of these things.

137
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:41,000
 I want to show you how we can lay out a NOR gate.

138
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:47,000
 And the basic idea of these things is that it's kind of like a NOT gate, and that's what's cool about it.

139
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:53,000
 Except there are two PMOS transistors at the top and two NMOS transistors at the bottom.

140
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:03,000
 The bottom set of transistors decide when it's connected to ground, and the top set of transistors decide when it's connected to five volts.

141
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:12,000
 And they work in kind of parallel and opposite to make sure that there's never a connection from the voltage to the ground.

142
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 It's either the ground to the output or the voltage to the output.

143
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 So let's do a real quick walkthrough of a NOR gate.

144
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:26,000
 So NOT OR. So right now we have inputs of one.

145
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:31,000
 Now we've made the input zero. So when it's zero, both are zeros, then the output is a one.

146
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:37,000
 And if any of them are one, either of them are one, then the output becomes zero.

147
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:43,000
 And so it's not that tricky. It sort of looks like an extended NOT gate.

148
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 In that basically we've got two PMOS transistors at the top.

149
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:58,000
 And if either of them are one, that blocks the flow of electricity from the five volts to the output.

150
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 And the same is true we have in parallel NMOS gates, where if either of them is on, that connects ground to the output.

151
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:14,000
 So you can see that when I have them both, with both of them on, both A and B on,

152
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:22,000
 you see that both of the NMOS transistors are conducting and so ground comes up.

153
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 But like if I just change one of them, you see that the five volts is flowing through the top PMOS, but it's being stopped by the second PMOS.

154
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:39,000
 And so that means that the plus five does not flow to the output.

155
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:48,000
 And looking at the NMOS transistors, you see that this one is not conducting, but the other one, the B input, is conducting.

156
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:53,000
 And so there is at least one path from the output to ground.

157
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:07,000
 If I flip these, you'll see that now that A is one and B is zero, you see that the plus five is blocked by the non-conducting first PMOS transistor.

158
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:16,000
 And the ground passes through the conducting NMOS transistor, the first NMOS, the A NMOS transistor.

159
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:23,000
 And so just kind of look at it, you see that what it is is really just kind of more not gates.

160
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:27,000
 It's either going to conduct eventually from the top or the bottom.

161
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:34,000
 And now we can have all the combinations of the inputs that work and by creating this structure.

162
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:41,000
 And so you could create a three input NOR gate, a four input NOR gate, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

163
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:46,000
 So this is just a look at an upcoming lecture and an upcoming tool that you're going to use.

164
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:53,000
 Now, once we have the abstraction of digital logic, we can start designing circuits using digital logic design.

165
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:57,000
 And all of a sudden, it just is a lot simpler and a lot less cluttered.

166
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:05,000
 So here is a NAND gate designed at the level of a gate with inputs and outputs, and you're going to like it.

167
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:09,000
 Well, we're not going to build complex circuits using transistors.

168
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 All we're trying to do right now is give you the mapping from transistors to gates so that later when we use gates,

169
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:20,000
 you just assume that it's OK that there are transistors underneath.

